description.text:
When fitting the Anti Z Wobble thingi (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1431036) I found that the distance between the object and the coupler was too small so I took some steps to "raise" the bed to give me more height between the ZWobble thing and the coupler.

  1. I raised the bed using these - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1490698
  2. Then I found that the leveling screw was not long enough. So I made these adjustable extenders - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1574094

  3. I found that the LM8UU bearings on the Y axis rods were starting to make grooves in the rod so I printed these blocks+bearings and included the bed raising in them - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1605437. There are 2 versions one with and one without the bed raising mod. The silence of the Y bearings is great and no more grooves. When they wear out I have a spare set already printed.

    I still needed a little more height so I made these to be fitted as shown. They "raise" the bed by 5 mm and fit without the motors touching the table. Sketchup file is included.

I also got rid of those Al couplers and printed these. Work beautifully with hardly any wobble - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1651349

title: Space-filling molecular models:  Aromatic expansion set

description.text:
When we say "aromatic" compounds, that doesn't necessarily mean they smell nice (most do have a distinctive scent, but like most chemicals you're not supposed to go out of your way to smell them). "Aromatic" is chemspeak for certain flat, ring-shaped compounds with alternating double bonds. The double bonds exist out of the plane of the ring and interact (delocalize) in such a way the it's as if all the atoms are connected by 1 1/2 bonds and the resulting compound is particularly stable. You usually see six-membered rings, most of them made of carbon. This also happens to five-membered rings, but at least one atom needs to be something other than carbon ("heterocyclic" in chemspeak). Frequently this is nitrogen, but other atoms can do this also. So, to make six-membered aromatic rings, use CarbonPH6 and NitrogenPH1. To make five-membered rings use Carbon5PH1 and Nitrogen5PH1 (there's a "5" on these to help tell them from the six-membered ones). Usually nitrogen can't bond to atoms outside the ring because generally all three bonds are taken up to make the ring bonds. Occasionally this isn't the case. In that case, use the appropriate carbon model and print it in your nitrogen color. (they're the same size and shape). You frequently get two rings joined together; this lets the delocalized electrons extend over both rings, which results in a particularly stable molecule. Use CarbonJPH1 to join two six-membered rings. For even more complicated compounds you may need CarbonIPH1 also because the double-carbon unit may not fit. To join a five and a six-membered ring together, use Carbon56PH2. You can have to joined five-membered rings, but they're rare and I felt lazy.

See the starter set (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1720048), the carbon expansion set (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1730299), the nitrogen expansion pack (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1753583), halogen expansion set (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1730099), and the sulfur and phosphorous expansion set (http://thingaverse.com/thing:2350618) for more useful elements.

title: Pikon personal portable photobooth
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update! I had to improve on the original version --

The Pikon logo is an original - everything else with this thing came from modding other people's designs.

I built a portable photobooth following the Make instructions here:

http://makezine.com/projects/raspberry-pi-photo-booth/

I used an electrical enclosure from Home depot, a jigsaw and some black spray paint:

http://www.homedepot.com/p/Square-D-125-Amp-Overhead-Underground-Ringless-Horn-Meter-Socket-UGHTRS101B/100152068

Most of the knobs and gewgaws on this, are directly from schlem's terrapin pinhole camera (I took the combined meshes and broke them into smaller files to make the knobs bigger):

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:728157

I found some old hotel air conditioning switches and mounted them on the enclosure. The one on the right controls the power, the one on the left controls nothing -- maybe I'll hook this to the GPIO and have it launch the selfie script.

I grabbed Jesse's pegboard AC plug mount http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:902305 and chopped off the pegs - this is glued on the inside of the enclosure to keep the adapter in place when you are on the road.

I modified Cheewee2000's flip top lens cap http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:656038 (a lot) to make the hinged cap for the side to allow to close it up when you are a'travelin'.

Finally I modified tilden's CPAP hose clamp http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:220972 (also a lot) to hold a Rii X1 in the enclosure.

http://www.riitek.com/product/mini/4.html

I decided that configuring Wifi everywhere I go can be maddening trying to use the touchscreen keyboard, and this little bluetooth unit works great.

The end result is a beefy, comically over-sized camera that is actually a touchscreen photobooth and big chunky satisfying knobs to control it on top. The kids love it, and the family gets to see all the selfies in real time through Google.

title: E3D BigBox - Dual Titan Main Parts (cleaned)

description.text:
This are the main parts of the Dual Titan design for the E3D BigBox just a bit cleaned.

There are two versions of the X carriage, one with a sensor mount for an inductive proximity sensor with an M18x1.5 thread.

What I did:

X carriage

  • removed the cable mounts on the back, mine always broke and I didn't use them anyways
  • fixed the hex nut cutouts for the endstop so they print better
  • changed the cutouts for the belt, on the left side more tooth for better grip, change the screw position so the belt has a tighter fit
  • filled the cable path for the endstop, didn't get the cable in and didn't use it
  • fixed and added fillets where they were obviously missing
  • filled the cutouts for a back fan mount, at least that's what I assumed they are for but there is not enough space to mount a fan on the back

X idler

  • also changed the belt mounts
  • moved the endstop screw 1.5mm to the back to have an even better position
  • fixed the big round cutout
  • made the hole for the back rod go through all, I was able to mount the X axis without removing the Y axis then with a little bending...

X motor mount

  • also changed the belt mounts
  • made the hole for the back rod go through all

description.text:
This is a lens cover hood combo. It was made using
sketchpunk's "Mechanical Iris" visit,like, and follow his page linked below for assembly instructions of the iris.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:773759
&
PrototypeProfessor's "Nikon 18-55 af Lens hood" you should also visit, like, and follow his page linked below for a video explaining the functionality of the lens hood he created. This design may not support some of the mentioned fish eye effects, but will work on making it fit.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1600188

This cover and hood combo was designed to fit
"Nikon DX AF-S NIKKOR 55-200mm1:4-5.6G ED" lens pictured above.
&
"Nikon DX AF-S NIKKOR 18-55mm1:3.5-5.6G ED"
two small screw hole are on the side of the base to allow added security if felt needed.

This design has not been tested with additional filters and lens effects fitted on the end of the camera anyone who cares to do so please let me know how it holds up and provide pictures because corrections can easily be made to add additional space between the "base" and the lens.

The Iris doesn't completely close a small pea sized hole it as far as is goes. However the leafs should provide enough support to handle light pokes and bumps.

This was made for fun and will not provide an airtight seal from dust, or water it is simply a semi function show piece.

and of course if anyone has any questions, or if having trouble with the print send me a message and I will do my best to help you out and correct any issues that arise.

Thanks

09.14.2016 - A design error in the "base" file has been fixed. The new "base" file has had the adapter rotated so the it sits square with the camera. The base has also had its side holes filled to make a more uniformed look and provide more protection .
The spacer file has also been modded to provide more protection and easier assembly.
Sorry for the inconvenient.

description.text: This is a small clip provides an easy way to secure the free end of component tape of a partially used 8mm reel. The clip goes on and comes off  easily. It keeps the component tape wrapped on the reel securly and protects the peel back cover.

This part was designed in Solidworks 2013 and went through some 30 of 40 insane iterations to get a design which worked reliably and met my requirements.  It's small enough to print lots and lots in a single pass.  
This particular part was designed from scratch in Solidworks 2013 then printed on an Ordbot Hadron Printer in ABS with a modified QU-BD stepstruder. It was printed using a 1.75 mm ABS filament with a layer thickness of .2 mm (200 microns) and an 85% fill factor with scaffolding support turned off.  
ABS Printing was performed at 235C on clear Monokote film over a heated glass bed at 110C for the first layer and 100C for all subsequent layers. Aquanet Extra Super Hold was sprayed on the Monokote to insure stick down. I've had no ABS stick down issues since I began using the above technique.

description.text:
My never ending quest to find a lasting articulated arm design has finally ended. I regularly use the PCB Workstation with Articulated Arms to hold my PCB projects. Unfortunately, all of the arms I have made with printed ball and socket joints quickly loosen to the point where they can hardly hold their own weight. I have tried several ball and socket designs and many filament types and I can't get any arms to last. That is until I found out about flexible coolant pipe.

Flexible coolant pipe is used in the metal fabrication industry to spray coolant over a work piece while machining. The pipes must be liquid tight so the fit between the ball and socket is very snug. They also are made from a durable plastic without the striations that cause 3D-printed joints to wear so fast. The pipes can be bought from Ebay and other places for cheap. I got my pipes for less than $1 USD each including shipping. It is best to get the type without the valve at the bottom since it is of no use. Here is an Ebay search link:

Search Ebay for flexible coolant pipes

The flexible coolant pipes I bought have 1/2"-20 threads at one end and a nozzle at the other end. The joints are very snug but you can remove pieces with pliers. I designed four adapters to fit the pipes to the PCB workstation:

  • Base Joint Adapter - This adapter is for mounting the pipe on the base plate and requires removal of the threaded piece on the pipe. The ball snaps into the bottom socket on the pipe.

  • Base Socket Adapter - This adapter is also for mounting the pipe on the base plate but it uses the existing threads on the pipe. This provides a stiffer and longer lasting joint. The inside of the socket is threaded 1/2"-20 so the pipe simply screws in. You may have to chase the threads with a bolt or tap depending on the material and your printer.

  • Ball & Socket Adapater - This adapter snaps onto the end of the pipe after the nozzle is removed. It adapts the larger ball on the pipes to the smaller ball used by the PCB workstation accessories.

  • Ball Insert Adapter - This adapter slides into the end of the pipe and has a ball sized for the PCB workstation accessories. This adapter provides a more durable connection to the accessories than using the ball & socket adapter. The shaft should be a tight fit into the pipe. You can use a drop of super glue to hold it in place if it starts working out.

All four adapters are done in OpenSCAD so you can customize them to fit whatever pipes you get. I proofed these using PLA and printed the final versions with PETG for extra durability.

title: Snowball iCE Mic Stand Repair Part - Rev A

description.text:
I just got a Snowball Ice Microphone and it is awesome...the stand it came with....not so awesome. The mic is supposed to thread into the base but the plastic threads were almost instantly ripped up and the mic doesn't safely stay put. Since the little tripod base unscrews, I was able to take off the damaged thread portion to retrofit my own. I designed this so the mic just sits on it, no locking...yet. I would like to revise this so the mic fits a little snugger and also come up with a way to lock it in. For now, this works.
FYI - Assembly is a little tricky. I hollowed out the part and there is a recessed hexagon inside the part to trap the locking nut. I used a 6-32 screw and nut, instead of a tapping screw (how it was originally designed). You just need to use a screwdriver or something to press down on the nut initially. Once it starts to engage you are good to go...

title: Tevo Black Widow - Z Endstop Adjustable

description.text:
Mount for Z end stop on Tevo Black Widow printer that allows for manual fine tuning of physical Z-offset.

Materials I used:

Parts for mounting sensor to sled:

  • M3x10 screw
  • M3 washer
  • M3 nut

Parts for adjustment mechanism

  • M3x25 screw
  • M3 locknut (The locknut serves to keep the screw from free spinning when the adjustment nut is turned.)
  • 8mm section of silicone tubing (a spring would work here as well)
  • M3 washer
  • M3 thumb screw nut

Parts for attaching mount to printer:

  • M4x8 screw (x2)
  • M4 washer (x2)
  • M4 drop-in t-nut (x2)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height, 0.4mm nozzle.

Infill:

45%

Notes:

There are two small pieces at the ends of the keyed slot in the "sled" part that will need to be cut off. I put these there so I could print with a brim and not have the brim go down the inside of the slot. I printed both parts at the same time with supports, but I think the sled would be better printed without supports while the mount needs supports for the keyed track that the sled will slide onto.
